commit.message:
Fix collapsing/expanding future node retry

Previously, when trying to collapse (or expand) an non-existing node,
liblarch would remember to do the operation when it sees the node being
added.
However, they pass the liblarch path object instead of the Gtk.TreePath
object, so PyGObject will complain about invalid type:

TypeError: argument path: Expected Gtk.TreePath, but got tuple

commit.message:
Fix pytest warnings

When runing pytest I got some warnings about deprecated function calls.
Here are most of the changes:

* replaced `GObject.MainLoop` for `GLib.MainLoop`
* Since version 3.11, calling threads_init is no longer needed, so I
removed this call. See: https://wiki.gnome.org/PyGObject/Threading
* replaced `GObject.idle_add` for `GLib.idle_add`
* replaced `assert_` for `assertTrue`

LSP warned me about some lines that were greater than 79 characters,
I think this may not be very important, but I have fixed this anyway.

Also, there was a warning about not using bare `execept` at the line 51
of the `watchdog.py` file. But I'm not really a python developer so
I wouldn't know how to fix it.

I ran the pytest again and I don't seem to have breaked anything.

commit.message:
Expliciting LGPLv3-or-later in the README file

I researched and found that to license the source code under LGPLv3-or-later
you just need to specify it in the source code header, but the license is the
same so I don't need to make any changes to the LICENSE file and the source
files already have the explicit "or any later version" in the header.

I'm just modifying the README file because Github doesn't have a way to tell
the person visiting the repository that the program is LGPLv3-or-later, it
just says LGPLv3, so I think the most effective way to specify it is to put
it in the README file.

Release version 3.0.1
Harmonize "CHANGELOG" with "debian/changelog"
debian: Updated changelog
debian: Bumped Standards-Version to 4.5.0

debian: Removed unnecessary X-Python3-Version header

From the Debian Python Library Style Guide[1]:

  The oldest supported version of Debian (as of 2018-05-03) includes
  python3.4, so if the minimum version is less than 3.4, there is no
  need to include X-Python3-Version.

 [1] https://wiki.debian.org/Python/LibraryStyleGuide#Python_versions
debian: Fixed typo in package description

debian: Fixed package description indentation

This fixes the description-starts-with-leading-spaces lintian warning.

debian: Reworded package synopsis line

The Debian package synopsis line (aka short description) has been
reworded, using the GitHub repo description, according to the Best
Packaging Practices chapter of the Debian Developer's Reference[1].

 [1] https://www.debian.org/doc/manuals/developers-reference/best-pkging-practices.en.html#the-package-synopsis-or-short-description

debian: Bump debhelper compatibility level to 10

Debhelper compatibility level 8 has been deprecated for quite a while
now; 10 is currently the oldest level that's not deprecated, and the
highest one natively supported by Debian `stretch` (aka `oldstable`).

(For the record, we could also jump straight to 12 without any changes
to the packaging.)
debian: Run test suite when building, using Xvfb

debian: Switch dh build system to pybuild

Pybuild[1] is the recommended[2] dh build system for Python 3 modules,
as python_distutils only supports Python 2.

As a bonus, since pybuild builds within a dedicated `.pybuild` directory
which it removes on cleanup, override_dh_auto_clean is no longer needed
and can be removed.

Also note that Build-Depends-Indep was folded back within Build-Depends,
as it is mostly useless for arch:all packages.

(Testing is disabled for the moment; the next commit will fix this.)

 [1] https://wiki.debian.org/Python/Pybuild
 [2] https://wiki.debian.org/Python/LibraryStyleGuide#Overview

Add "# noqa" to two the gi version requirement to avoid CI failures

This is meant to prevent the CI suite failing on PEP8 from commit 282870
